es must match the expected endpoint JSON shape.\n25:  - Azure/Microsoft Foundry passwordless paths rely on optional azure-identity classes and are not needed for normal OpenAI-provider coverage.\n34:  - You may inspect the repository only to learn local test style and structure.\n38:  - Every individual test must complete in under 60 seconds. Use bounded waits and short client/server/executor timeouts, close all resources, and avoid sleeps or background work that can deadlock or keep the JVM alive.\n44:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_start\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"Role: You are an expert JVM test engineer specializing in high-coverage integration testing for external libraries.\\n\\nTask:\\nYou need to generate comprehensive tests for the library defined by these Maven coordinates: org.springframework.ai:spring-ai-openai:2.0.0-RC2.\\n\\nIssue-Requested Metadata:\\nNo reporter-provided missing metadata context was supplied.\\n\\nLibrary Preparation Preflight:\\nLibrary preparation preflight produced setup context.\\n\\nSummary: No extra Maven dependency or Docker image is required, but meaningful model-call coverage needs tests to avoid the default live OpenAI endpoint and real API-key lookup.\\n\\nAgent guidance:\\nFor tests that invoke OpenAiChatModel, OpenAiEmbeddingModel, OpenAiImageModel, OpenAiAudioSpeechModel, OpenAiAudioTranscriptionModel, or OpenAiModerationModel, configure options programmatically with a local OpenAI-compatible base URL, e.g. .baseUrl(\\\"http://127.0.0.1:<port>/v1\\\"), and .apiKey(\\\"\\\") for no-auth mode or a dummy key. Serve minimal OpenAI-compatible responses from an in-process JDK HttpServer rather than calling https://api.openai.com/v1 or relying on OPENAI_API_KEY. If testing Spring property-based configuration, set spring.ai.openai.base-url and spring.ai.openai.api-key to equivalent local test values. Avoid Azure/Microsoft Foundry/GitHub Models environment-detection paths unless intentionally covering them.\\n\\nRisks:\\n- The OpenAI Java SDK response parsers are strict enough that local stub responses must match the expected endpoint JSON shape.\\n- Azure/Microsoft Foundry passwordless paths rely on optional azure-identity classes and are not needed for normal OpenAI-provider coverage.\\n\\nRules:\\n- Write tests in `Java` under the module's existing `src/test/java` tree.\\n- Follow idiomatic `Java` coding conventions.\\n- Don't duplicate tested features.\\n- Use only the library's public API, no direct reflection or serialization.\\n- Modify only the test file. Update build.gradle only if required to add missing classpath dependencies or runtime args.\\n- Use only the features from the provided library version and avoid all deprecated APIs. Additional test dependencies are allowed only if they are necessary to exercise the tested library meaningfully and cannot be replaced with standard JDK or already-present dependencies.\\n- You may inspect the repository only to learn local test style and structure.\\n- If you are unsure about the library's API, look it up on the internet.\\n- All top-level test classes must be public.\\n- Do not compile or run tests yourself. The workflow will do that externally.\\n- Every individual test must complete in under 60 seconds. Use bounded waits and short client/server/executor timeouts, close all resources, and avoid sleeps or background work that can deadlock or keep the JVM alive.\\n- After generating the tests, do NOT attempt to compile, run, or verify them. We will handle test execution externally.\\n- Reporter issue context identifies what is missing; infer the relevant public API paths from that context and cover them in tests.\\n\"}], \"timestamp\": 1782510376120}}\n45:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"Role: You are an expert JVM test engineer specializing in high-coverage integration testing for external libraries